data.content:
All three code snippets hit EF Core 10 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer accepts `Expression<Func<…>>`

The setters parameter is now a plain `Func`, so hand-built expression trees won't compile. Replace with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

All that `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` machinery is no longer needed.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Sibling complex types now get uniquified columns.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared one `Street` column (silent data corruption). EF 10 appends a number (`Street`, `Street1`). To keep the old names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; it now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

⚠️ Both changes will generate new migrations that rename/add columns. If you have existing data, either add explicit `.HasColumnName()` calls to preserve the old names, or create a migration and test carefully.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (supports constant-redaction in logs). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual SQL sent to the DB
    }
}
```

Update all other methods on the interface similarly (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
